    "description": {
      "summary": "The Nuppeppō (also written as Nuppefuhōfu or Nuppehō) is a grotesque yōkai from Japanese folklore described as a large, blob-like creature made of decomposing human flesh.",
      "full": "The Nuppeppō (also written as Nuppefuhōfu or Nuppehō) is a grotesque yōkai from Japanese folklore described as a large, blob-like creature made of decomposing human flesh. Its name is onomatopoetic, suggesting something soft, squishy, and malleable. Typically depicted as a flesh-colored mass roughly the size and shape of a human but without distinct features beyond rudimentary facial indentations, the Nuppeppō is characterized primarily by its overwhelmingly putrid odor of rotting flesh. Despite its horrifying appearance and smell, the creature is generally harmless, wandering aimlessly through abandoned temples, graveyards, and desolate areas. In some traditions, consuming its flesh grants immortality, connecting it to Chinese concepts of immortality elixirs."
    },
